TASK 1 - LAN TOPOLOGIES & NETWORK DEVICES
LAN (Local Area Network)
• Connects devices within a limited area (Home, Office, School, Building).
• Used for sharing files, printers, Internet and resources.
• Topology = Physical/Logical design of a network.
STAR TOPOLOGY
• Every device connects to a central Switch/Hub.
• Most common and highly scalable.
• Advantages:
•	Fast and reliable.
•	Easy to add new devices.
•	One cable failure affects only one device.
• Disadvantages:
•	Expensive.
•	Central Switch is the Single Point of Failure (SPOF).
BUS TOPOLOGY
• All devices share one Backbone Cable.
• Advantages:
•	Cheap and easy to install.
•	Requires less cabling.
• Disadvantages:
•	Backbone cable failure stops entire network.
•	Traffic bottleneck.
•	Difficult troubleshooting.
RING TOPOLOGY
• Devices connect in a circular loop.
• Data travels in one direction through other devices.
• Advantages:
•	Less network congestion than Bus.
•	Easy fault detection.
• Disadvantages:
•	One cable/device failure breaks the entire network.
•	Data may travel through multiple devices, increasing delay.
SWITCH
• Layer 2 networking device.
• Connects devices inside a LAN.
• Uses MAC Address Table to forward data only to the correct destination.
• Faster and more secure than a Hub.
ROUTER
• Layer 3 networking device.
• Connects different networks (LAN ↔ Internet).
• Performs Routing (selects the best path for packets).
EXTRA CONCEPTS
• Routing = Process of forwarding packets between networks.
• Redundancy = Multiple communication paths for reliability.
• Bottleneck = Heavy traffic causing slow communication.
• Scalability = Ability to expand a network easily.
• SPOF (Single Point of Failure) = One failed component can stop the network.
TASK 2 - SUBNETTING
• Subnetting = Dividing one large network into smaller networks (Subnets).
• Improves Security, Performance, Network Management, and Efficiency.
• Subnet Mask = 32-bit number used to divide networks.
• IPv4 Subnet Mask Range = 0–255 per octet.
IMPORTANT ADDRESSES
• Network Address = Identifies the network (e.g., 192.168.1.0).
• Host Address = Identifies a device within the network.
• Default Gateway = Device (usually Router) that forwards data to other networks (commonly .1 or .254).
EXTRA CONCEPT
• Devices in the same subnet communicate directly.
• Devices in different subnets communicate through the Default Gateway.
TASK 3 - ARP (ADDRESS RESOLUTION PROTOCOL)
• ARP = Address Resolution Protocol.
• Maps an IP Address (Logical Address) to a MAC Address (Physical Address).
• Every device stores known mappings in an ARP Cache.
ARP PROCESS
1.	ARP Request → "Who has this IP?"
2.	ARP Reply → "I have this IP. Here's my MAC."
KEY TERMS
• ARP Cache = Stores IP ↔ MAC mappings.
• IP Address = Logical Identifier.
• MAC Address = Physical Identifier.
TASK 4 - DHCP (DYNAMIC HOST CONFIGURATION PROTOCOL)
• DHCP automatically assigns IP addresses to devices joining a network.
• Eliminates manual IP configuration.
DHCP PROCESS (DORA)
1.	DHCP Discover → Client searches for DHCP Server.
2.	DHCP Offer → Server offers an IP Address.
3.	DHCP Request → Client accepts the offered IP.
4.	DHCP ACK → Server confirms and assigns the IP.
EXTRA CONCEPT
• DORA = Discover → Offer → Request → Acknowledge (Easy way to remember DHCP process).
KEY TERMS
• DHCP = Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol.
• Automatic IP Assignment.
• Prevents IP Address conflicts.
ROOM SUMMARY
LAN → Star | Bus | Ring → Switch → Router → Routing → Subnetting → Network Address → Host Address → Default Gateway → ARP (IP ↔ MAC) → DHCP (DORA)
